Q45. What are sets in Python?
In Python, a set is an unordered collection of unique elements. It is defined using curly braces {} or the set() constructor.
Sets are mutable, which means that you can add or remove elements from a set after it has been created.
Sets are similar to lists and tuples in Python, but they have some important differences:
Sets are unordered, which means that you cannot rely on the order of elements in a set.
Sets can only contain unique elements. If you try to add a duplicate element to a set, it will be ignored.
Sets are mutable, which means that you can add or remove elements from a set after it has been created.

Q46. How can you create a set?
can create a set using either curly braces {} or the set() constructor. 

